    <h4 class="modal-title">Learn</h4>
    <p>In the recent decades, India has made commendable progress in the area of providing access to schooling and the subsequent increase in the enrolment rates across the nation is laudatory. Primary school enrolment in India has been successful largely due to various programs and drives to increase enrolment even in remote areas such as the Right to Education (RTE) and the flagship Sarva Shiksha Abhiyaan scheme of the central government. With enrolment reaching at least 96 percent since 2009, where girls make up 56 percent of new students between 2007 and 2013, it is clear that many problems of access to schooling have been addressed. Improvements to infrastructure have been a priority to achieve this under RTE and India now has 1.4 million schools and 7.7 million teachers so that 98 percent of habitations have a primary school (class I-V) within one kilometre.</p>
    <p>However, despite these positive statistics, low learning outcomes has remained a massive challenge for the state and central governments (ASER, 2014). In the absence of nationwide data on urban government schools, the Annual Status of Education Report (ASER) show the dismal numbers which are really concerning. According to ASER 2014, published by education non-profit organization Pratham Education Foundation, the proportion of all children in Class 5 who can read a Class 2 text has improved by 1 percentage point from 2013—48.1% children of Class 5 could read a class 2 text in 2014 against 47% in the previous year.</p>
    <p>With studies revealing the need to shift the focus from merely providing inputs in terms of both infrastructure and human resources toward the quality of teaching materials, importance of teacher-student relationship and methodology of teaching, efforts must now be concentrated on improving the below par learning outcomes of the country’s students.</p>
